{"status":"success","result":"Okay, good foundation. Here's my honest read of the full history:\n\n*What's impressive:*\nThe entire system went from scratch to v0.1.0 — including the semantic classifier I was recommending — in a single day. That's fast. Claude CLI shipped exactly the right thing.\n\n*What the changelog history reveals:*\nVersions 0.0.15 through 0.0.29 all have identical \"Fresh off the press\" notes. That's not a style choice — the changelog tooling was broken or ignored during a stretch of active development. Means there's a gap in the record of what actually changed during that window. Worth knowing.\n\n*Where v0.1.0 leaves us — the open questions I'd prioritize:*\n\n• *Is the classifier actually working?* We shipped it but there's no validation. Do we know qwen3:4b is routing correctly? The 8s fallback to regex means silent degradation is possible — and invisible.\n\n• *The feedback loop is still missing.* You asked earlier whether binary feedback could improve the Secretary over time. The answer is yes, but nothing is capturing that signal yet. That's the highest-value next feature.\n\n• *Silent failures are still undetected.* Auto-escalation catches models that apologize. It doesn't catch models that confidently answer wrong. That's the scarier failure mode.\n\n*My first recommendation as CTO:*\nBefore adding new capabilities, instrument what exists. Add logging on classifier decisions — what model was chosen, what task_type, what complexity — so we have real data on whether the routing is working before we build on top of it.\n\nWhat's Claude CLI planning to tackle next?","newSessionId":"9ab085a0-060d-41ae-b3d8-a97f4d571171"}
